fix hashes for objects with __eq__ In general, objects that define a custom __eq__ should have a custom
__hash__, to ensure that equal objects have the same hash.  This is
required in python 3, but should be followed even in python-2 for
correct behavior

objects given a new hash:
    pymel.core.system.Namespace
    pymel.util.arguments.AddedKey
    pymel.util.arguments.RemovedKey
    pymel.util.arguments.ChangedKey

- more robost retry on crash:
  - formerly had situation where kept trying the same command over and over,
    and crashing (psdEditTextureFile)
  - now, writes a crashJournal text file, which should prevent a command
    from being run if it was the first run command last time, and it crashed
  - for non-first-command-crashes, we should always update the processed
    examples for the other commands before the crash
- we now write the "in-case-it-crashes" intermediate results into a temp dir
  - this makes for much faster iteration, as we just write one file per
    command, instead of rewriting the cache for every command, which gets
    progressively slower as the cache size grows
  - if we DO crash, we gather up the temp dir contents, and write them to
    the processed crash

LazyLoadModule - now automatically subclasses this prevents pollution of the LazyLoadModule class's namespace, which
would be shared by all LazyLoadModules.  This is what happened with
pymel.core.uitypes - it installed it's lazy-load attrs on the base class,
LazyLoadModule.  pymel.core.nodetypes used it's own subclass -
NodetypesLazyLoadModule - but since that inherited from LazyLoadModule, the
net effect was that nodetypes had all the uitypes accessible from it's
namespace.

Since this bug has been out there for a while, I'm manually installing all
these uitypes in the nodetypes namespace to preserve backwards
compatibility... but we may try to remove these at some point.

(from MEL), because they operate on quaternions, which are what the

useful to give direct access.

formerly, getRotateOrientation was set to disable, and 'useName' of
_getRotateOrientation, which had a couple of problems - subclasses
still had getRotateOrientation / setRotateOrientation, but not only
that, the setRotateOrientation had it's pair set to
_getRotateOrientation, which didn't exist! Also, we're eliminated the
unused "space" argument.

we may either address these issues in the future, and re-enable saving,
or make this dialog read-only (ie, disable 'editable' in all UI
elements), or just remove this UI altogether

LazyLoad module: fix for __dir__ to inspect type's parents too this is because of a bit of a bug with LazyLoadModule -
pymel.core.uitypes and pymel.core.nodetypes both use a LazyLoadModule,
but nodetypes subclassess it (NodetypesLazyLoadModule), while uitypes
doesn't. this means that the nodetypes module effectively has access to
all the uitypes, due to the fact the LazyLoadModule needs to install
it's members on the CLASS.

We should fix this at some point by making uitypes use a subclasses,
and making LazyLoadModule an abstract base class that can't be
instantiated directly

nodeclass.py: api methods with no args are never undoable ...because the api undo system is based around using a corresponding
"getter" to get the args, and then setting them with "this" function.
Hoewver, with no args, there is no way to set it to the results
returned by the getter.

Technically, an api function with no args could be it's own do and undo,
if it was a "toggle" type function... however, we currently have no way of
detecting that. So we assume a func with no args is not undoable.

This has no change in behavior, since no functions that were actually
wrapped were detected as "undoable" if they had no args.

nodetypes: import uitypes, for backward compatibility there was a bug in the way that LazyLoadModule was used:
because data descriptors require items to be installed
at the class level, and an instance of LazyLoadModule
was used directly in the pymel.core.uitypes module, this
meant that all it's lazy members were installed directly
on the LazyLoadModule base class.  Thus,
pymel.core.nodetypes inherited them (even though IT used
a subclass, NodetypesLazyLoadModule, so IT'S members
weren't visible to uitypes).
The fix would have been to enforce creation of
subclasses, probably throuhg LazyLoadModule.__new__;
however, as the class isn't used anymore, not bothering
with this fix.

Debated not including these members, but there
is a decent chance someone was using them, even if on
accident, so we decided to include them

stubs: trigger import of a module if the parent module of a class's base class is in maybe_modules ie, in flux.ae.template, had:

import pymel.core as pm
class Template(pm.uitypes.AETemplate):
    ...

the "import pymel.core as pm" added an entry to maybe_modules... then when looking up the classname for
pm.uitypes.AETemplate, pymel.core.uitypes / pm.uitypes wasn't in maybe_modules (though pm was) - and
the import statement didn't get triggered

now we check if the parent module (in this case, pymel.core / pm) is in maybe_modules, and use it's import
text if so.

Note that (to be safe) we still need to add a "import pymel.core.uitypes" line, to ensure that ".uitypes" exists
on pymel.core (though in this particular case, this isn't necessary, in general, it might be)

Python root logging level set to DEBUG The logging module states that the root logger has to have a level specified. In the logging module, root = Logger(WARNING). However in the pymel.conf file, logger_root level is set to NOTSET. [logger_root] level=NOTSET handlers= remove_existing_handlers=False Options: Modify the pymel.conf file to set logger_root level=WARNING Modify pymel.plogging.pymelLogFileConfig() to set the root logger back to the original level (if set to NOTSET) Option2 should be more robust and allow for user configurable pymel.conf files while correcting the bug in the root logger level. Here is the code to add to plogging.py     root_logger_level = root.level   # store off the root logger level, to restore back at the bottom of this function         # if root logger level not explicitly set in the pymel.conf file,
        # then set it back to the original value.  The root logger always
        # has to have a level.

We recently investigated the exceptions that are thrown when we launch Maya and found out that there is one exception coming from a PyMEL script. In pymel/api/plugins.py, we found that you are trying to pass a non-existing flag to the pluginInfo command. The flag is:
'contextCommand': {}, # currently no pluginInfo flag for this in any version, but I'm an optimist...

We investigated the matter, and found out that the tool flag is doing what you probably are looking for. It will return the tool context commands. I have to admit the flag name is a bit confusing, and maybe you thought that it would return the tool commands proper. It turns out that tool commands are already part of the regular commands and are returned when you use the command flag (you already do).
So long story short we replaced contextCommand with tool in plugins.py on our side, and it got rid of that one exception.

some more reworking of the reference classes and functions.  the reference class now uses a referenceNode as it's basis, because if we store the refNode as a PyNode, we can quickly and automatically get any updates made to its name.  almost any reference info can be queried using the refNode (withou resorting to a path, which might change without us knowing), including resolved and unresolved paths.  namespaces are still the one weak spot, for which we must first get a path with copy number.  the use of a refNode precludes the need for the caching system, so long as using referenceQuery to get file paths when they are needed provides adequate performance. in general, because almost all the internal queries use the refNode, there should be little need for the paths, except for displaying to the user. git-svn-id: https://pymel.googlecode.com/svn/trunk@1129 64d93f2f-123f-0410-81d3-998474c5a783

reorganized the cache system onto a class.  i feel there may be a fundamental flaw in this system because namespaces can be edited, so two references could have their namespaces swapped and the cached result would come up wrong.  previously, caching did not take nested references into account. i have tried to add this, but it seems that the api callback happens too soon and i get an error.  for now the api callbacks have been disabled, and the caching mechanism is forced refreshed each time. git-svn-id: https://pymel.googlecode.com/svn/trunk@1125 64d93f2f-123f-0410-81d3-998474c5a783

Changed the way Singleton classes behave to be more in line with the way I assumed they worked (and it seems other people have been using them):         If arguments are passed into the constructor, then a new instance will be created (and initialized using
        the arguments); if the class is called with no arguments, then the existing instance will be returned (or
        created if it has never been instantiated before).
        
Previously, if we did

class MySing(Singleton, Dict): pass

MySing({'A':1})
MySing({'B':2})

...then MySing would now be {'A':1, 'B':2} - ie, calling the constructor only UPDATES, not re-initializes

If you were actually AWARE of this, and making use of it, my apologies...

improved api wrapping.  changed apicls to __apicls__.  the very important distinction here is that, currently, if a class provides the __apicls__ attribute instead of apicls, the wrap will be a 'proxy' wrap, meaning the new class won't actually inherit from the provided apicls, but will simply delegate to it.  it become far too much work trying to have Node classes inherit from MFn classes, with little advantage.  using __getattribute__ to 'remove' unwanted or renamed methods complicates and slows down everything, and provides more confusing error messages due to the traceback pointing into pymel.  the "ture regarding naming, perhaps we should standardize on __apicls__ and __apiproxycls__ or something to that effect.  for now, i wanted to avoid breaking all of olivier's stuff that relies on 'apicls'.

Fixed a bug where, on loading a scene that requires a plugin, extra junk nodes were created by the 'dgtrick' Updated mayaReservedTypes Allowed rebuilding of all but information built from api docs (ie, apiClassInfo), so I could build an updated         mayaApi2008.bin Full list of changes:

api.conversions:
    consolidated code for doing dgMod / dagMod 'trick' into '_makeDgModGhostObject' function
        also, we now call dagMod/dgMod.deleteNode for created nodes, as otherwise we will litter scene with
        'junk nodes' when loading a scene that requires a plugin; also, try dgMod BEFORE dagMod, as this
        avoids creating a junk transform
    _buildMayaReservedTypes: updated plugin node types, misc other additions
    _parentFn: made dagMod/dgMod args mandatory (since no default ones were actually created)
    _buildApiTypeHierarchy: added apiClassInfo kwarg, so we can reuse an existing apiClassInfo
    _buildApiCache: added rebuildAllButClassInfo kwarg:
        Set 'rebuildAllButClassInfo' to True to force rebuilding of all info BUT apiClassInfo -
        this is useful for versions < 2009, as these versions cannot parse the api docs; by setting
        this to False, you can rebuild all other api information.

core.windows:
    changed wrapper type from MetaMayaNodeWrapper to MetaMayaUIWrapper

core.pmtypes.factories:
    Redid MetaMayaWrapper hierarchy: made _MetaMayaCommandWrapper a base

Added pmcmds module, which wraps the commands in maya.cmds to accept PyNode arguments, for versions prior to 2009 Some reworking of functionFactory to work with pmcmds / reduce code duplication Misc bugfixes... Full list of changes:

Made core modules import mayahook.pmcmds instead of maya.cmds
     (changed animation, general, language, rendering, system, and windows modules)

__init__:
	Added final import at end of pymel.__init__ to make sure pymel.cmds == maya.cmds

core.animation:
	_constraint: fixed bug with new weight query syntax
	made various constraints use _constraint to generate them
	
core.general:
	removed various calls to stringify, as no longer necessary (stringify-ing is handled in pmcmds)
	disconnectAttr: fixed bug with disconnecting all connections (ie, destination==None)
	listConnections: modified makePairs to use util.pairIter
	moved def. of ProxyUnicode to util.utilitytypes, so it can be accesed by util.arguments / mayahook.pmcmds
	PyNode.nodeType: fixed
	Attribute.__apimobject__: fixed
	Attribute.__apimfn__: small clarity, code consolidation change
	Attribute.nodeName: duplicate definition removed
	Attribute.type: now returns u"message" if the attribute is a message attribute
	Attribute.isMessageType: added method
	IkHandle: added class, with jointList and endEffector methods
	
core.language:
	conditionExists: added function to test existence of a condition (ie, the type of condition tested by isTrue, not a condition node)
	
factories.factories:
	getInheritance: now properly deletes node when it is itself a transform node, but has no parents
	_addCmdDocs: now tries to lookup cmdInfo if not fed it, and checks that the function isn't a runtime command
	functionFactory: now imports commands from pmcmds instead of maya.cmds by default
		fixed bug with trying to create unicode function names
		better handling of non-function callable objects
		no longer rename functions in-place (would result in mismatch between module's __dict__ and function's __name__)
		refactored code for clarity / less code duplication
	pluginLoaded/UnloadedCallback: updates pmcmds
	
mayahook.mayautils:
	getRunningMayaVersion: refactored duplicate code into this new function
	mayaIsRunning: code clarity wrapper for getRunningMayaVersion
	getMayaExecutable: keyword argument name changed from 'batch' to 'commandLine' for clarity
		checks to make sure it doesn't return python executable (if it did, _getVersionStringFromExecutable will hang)
	mayaDocsLocation: now uses mayaIsRunning for clarity / avoid a catch-all except
	mayaInit: now uses getRunningMayaVersion / mayaIsRunning
	
mayahook.pmcmds:
	New module!
	wraps the commands in maya.cmds to accept PyNode arguments, for versions prior to 2009
	
mayahook.test_pmcmds:
	New module!
	various unittests to make sure PyNode args are stringified
	
util.arguments:
	isIterable: now correctly checks for objects that implement __getitem__, but not __iter__
	stringify: heavily modified for use in pmcmds
		now has optional keyword for recursion limiting
		can now maintain dictionaries, instead of converting to a list (and therefore losing values)
		can now be told to only stringify objects that are instances of specified classes
	stringifyPyNodeArgs: new decorator which will convert any PyNode arguments to unicode strings
	argsToPyNodes: decorator generator used to convert arguments INTO PyNodes (ie, opposite of stringifyPyNodeArgs)
	pairIter: new function which iterates over a list in 'pairs' - used to process results of listConnections

util.arrays:
	Vector.projectionOnto: new method to find the projection of one vector onto another
	
util.testingutils:
	new module!
	TestCaseExtended: new class, extends unittest.TestCase, contains msic. useful methods 
	permutations: (should be moved to util.math?)

util.test_testingutils:
    new module!
    unittests for testingutils

util.utilitytypes:
    ProxyUnicode moved here so it can be accessed from util.arguments / mayahook.pmcmds
